article.headline: Liberty win 6 of last 8
article.linkText: Liberty rally from 15 down to beat Sting
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- Coming off the WNBA's monthlong Olympic break,
the New York Liberty were a little rusty in the first half. They
regrouped nicely in the second half and completed a season sweep of
the Charlotte Sting.

Crystal Robinson had seven of her 16 points during a 17-4
second-half run and rallied the Liberty to a 56-52 win over the
Charlotte Sting at Radio City Music Hall on Thursday night.

"I thought the defense was the difference," Liberty guard
Becky Hammon said. "We just had to run our offense and stay with
it. We did that in the second half and that is why we looked like a
totally different team."

Trailing by 13, New York went on its game-turning run and tied
the game at 46 with 4:30 left. Robinson had a four-point play and
the tying 3-pointer during the run.

"It was huge," Liberty interim coach Pat Coyle said of the
four-point play. "It was the turning point of the game. It really
got the fans into it and got us into it."

Hammon made two free throws and a fastbreak layup to give the
Liberty their first lead of the game at 50-48 with 3:17 remaining.
After Tynesha Lewis' jumper tied the game with 2:50 left, New York
sealed the game at the free-throw line, going 6-for-6.

La'Keshia Frett gave New York the lead for good at 52-50 with
1:41 remaining, and Robinson secured the win with 13.7 seconds
left.

"Give New York credit, they fought hard and made plays down the
stretch and we didn't," Sting coach Trudi Lacey said. "We
couldn't execute down the stretch. We made some costly defensive
errors and costly turnovers."

Hammon and Frett added 10 points apiece for the Liberty, who won
for the sixth time in eight games and beat the Sting 4-0 in the
season series. New York outscored Charlotte 20-10 in the paint in
the second half and 30-28 for the game.

Three-time Olympian Dawn Staley and Charlotte Smith-Taylor led
the Sting with 13 points each, and Tammy Sutton-Brown had a
game-high eight rebounds.

New York stretched its lead over Charlotte to 1½ games in the
Eastern Conference, and remained perfect in three games at the
famed music hall.

"The race is so tight we cannot afford to slip up, especially
at home," Hammon said. "It was important to come out and start
off with a win."

Charlotte was 1-for-2 from the line while the Liberty finished
13-for-18.

The Sting took a 34-21 lead into halftime, led by 11 points from
Staley and nine from Smith-Taylor. Charlotte, which lost for the
seventh time in 10 games, shot 54 percent in the opening period.

New York shot just 29 percent (8-for-28) in the first half.

The Liberty played without centers Ann Wauters and Tari
Phillips. Wauters, averaging 6.3 points and 3.1 rebounds, is out
for the season because of a stress fracture in her right foot. She
is scheduled to undergo surgery in her native Belgium on Friday.
Phillips, still recovering from a broken right hand, is expected to
miss the next 2-to-3 weeks.

Liberty forward Elena Baranova, a member of the bronze
medal-winning Russian team, and Staley, a gold medalist on the U.S.
team, were honored before the game.

The Liberty have two home games left at Radio City due to the
Republican National Convention being held at Madison Square Garden.
New York won't return to the Garden until its regular-season finale
on Sept. 19 against Washington.
